At all events on the 6th of June, 1335, at York he restored the Great Seal to the King, who transferred it to John stratford, the Archbishop of Canterbury.¹ The attention of the King and uation was at this time chiefly concentrated upon foreign politics and the claim put forward by Edward to the French Crovn. The keenest and coolest intellects of the age were required for the tasks of diplomacy, and the choice of the sovereign again fell upon De Bury. The next few years of the Bishop's life were mainly devoted to this service, in the course of which he thrice visited Paris and spent some time in Flanders, Hainault, and Germany.
